    "### 4.12.2 Resampling Decision and Rationale\n",
    "\n",
    "**Strategy chosen:** SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why SMOTE over simple oversampling?** Simple duplication copies exact minority samples, which causes the model to memorise specific data points and overfit. SMOTE creates synthetic examples by interpolating between existing minority samples in feature space, producing more diverse training examples.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why not undersampling?** Undersampling discards majority class data. With our dataset size (~4,800 training rows), losing data would reduce the model's ability to learn patterns in the majority class.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Leakage prevention:** SMOTE was applied only to the training set. Validation and test sets remain untouched and reflect the true class distribution the model will encounter in production.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Modelling plan:**\n",
    "- We will train each model **twice** — once on the original training data and once on the SMOTE-resampled data — and compare performance on the unchanged validation set.\n",
    "- If the original distribution is already balanced (<1.5:1), the SMOTE version serves as a robustness check rather than a necessity.\n",
    "- Models also support `class_weight='balanced'` as an alternative to resampling — this will be tested during model development.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Datasets available for modelling:**\n",
