    "### 4.13.1 Pipeline Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "| Pipeline | Models | Steps | Leakage Safe |\n",
    "|---|---|---|---|\n",
    "| A (Linear) | Logistic Regression, SVM, KNN | Median impute → RobustScaler → One-hot encode (drop first) | ✅ Fit on train only |\n",
    "| B (Tree) | Random Forest, XGBoost | Median impute → One-hot encode (drop first) | ✅ Fit on train only |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why two pipelines?** Tree-based models split on thresholds and are invariant to feature scale. Forcing unnecessary scaling adds complexity without benefit. Linear and distance-based models require scaled inputs for stable gradient convergence and fair distance computation.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why `drop='first'` in OneHotEncoder?** Dropping one level per categorical feature avoids multicollinearity (the dummy variable trap), which is important for Logistic Regression where correlated features inflate coefficient variance.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why `remainder='drop'`?** Any column not listed in `numerical_cols` or `categorical_cols` (including CustomerID and the two constant columns) is automatically excluded. This acts as a safety net against accidentally leaking identifiers or noise into the model.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Reproducibility:** Both fitted pipelines are saved via `joblib`. In production or future notebooks, loading the saved pipeline ensures identical preprocessing without re-fitting — any new data passes through the exact same transformations learned from the training set.\n",
    "\n",
    "**From this point forward**, all modelling code will use:\n",
    "- `X_train_linear`, `X_val_linear`, `X_test_linear` for linear/distance models\n",
    "- `X_train_tree`, `X_val_tree`, `X_test_tree` for tree-based models\n",
    "- `y_train`, `y_val`, `y_test` remain unchanged across both pipelines"
   ]
  },
