    "### 5.8.1 Feature Importance Findings\n",
    "\n",
    "**Point-Biserial:** Shows linear association between each numeric feature and the binary target. Features with high |r| values are strong linear predictors. Features with |r| < 0.05 and non-significant p-values may contribute little to linear models.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Cramér's V:** Measures association strength between categorical features and the target. Values above 0.3 indicate strong association, 0.1–0.3 moderate, below 0.1 weak. This tells us whether campaign channel or type meaningfully relates to conversion.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Mutual Information:** Captures both linear and non-linear dependencies. Features ranked highly here but low in point-biserial may have non-linear relationships with the target — these are features where tree-based models may outperform logistic regression.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Redundancy check:** Any feature pair with Pearson correlation > 0.9 from Section 5.1 would be flagged for potential removal. Perfect correlation (1.0) would indicate data leakage or duplicate columns.\n",
    "\n",
    "These rankings will be compared against model-derived feature importances after training (Section 6) to validate whether the EDA predictions hold."
