    "### 7.4.1 Decision Tree Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "**Overfitting behaviour:** The gap between train and validation F1 widens as depth increases. Unlimited depth memorises training data. The best depth balances complexity and generalisation.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Interpretability:** Unlike Logistic Regression, Decision Trees produce human-readable rules (e.g. \"if ClickThroughRate > 0.12 and EmailOpens > 3 → predict Converted\"). These can be shared directly with marketing stakeholders.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Feature importance:** Gini importance shows which features the tree relies on most for splitting. Compare this with the LR coefficients from Section 7.3 — agreement between methods strengthens confidence in those features.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Limitations:** Single trees are unstable — small data changes can produce very different splits. This motivates ensemble methods (Random Forest, XGBoost) which aggregate many trees for robust predictions. These are tested next."
   ]
